TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bernanke, Ben S.
AU  - Carey, Kevin
T1  - Nominal Wage Stickiness and Aggregate Supply in the Great Depression*
PY  - 1996
Y1  - 1996/08/01
DO  - 10.2307/2946674
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 111
IS  - 3
SP  - 853
EP  - 883
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Building on earlier work by Eichengreen and Sachs, we use data for 22 countries to study the role of wage stickiness in propagating the Great Depression. Recent research suggests that monetary shocks, transmitted internationally by the gold standard, were a major cause of the Depression. Accordingly, we use money supplies and other aggregate demand shifters as instruments to identify aggregate supply relationships. We find that nominal wages adjusted quite slowly to falling prices, and that the resulting increases in real wages depressed output. These findings leave open the question of why wages were so inertial in the face of extreme labor market conditions.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2946674
ER  - 



